</font><P><P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#000000><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/urhad.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rhad</A></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Forum Apprentice</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#ffffff>11/27/00</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#ffffff>4:30:01 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Micon - I think you're pretty much right</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">  Based on the way NPCs have worked in the past in the game (and in fact in all other situations presently as well) there are only 2 things that can affect what an NPC says to you.  Which NPC it is, and the faction.<br>
  It seems pretty clear to me that the &quot;first&quot; Arantir is a combination of all the Shaman Merchant's quests, but with some different keywords (including &quot;hail&quot;).  This is probably for two purposes.  Clearness (since everything is supposed to go to &quot;Arantir&quot; but technicly the shaman chick IS Arantir), and faction.  The shaman vendor is based on the shaman guild faction, and thus every response/quest she gives is based entirely on that faction as well.  This is why a lot of people can't hand the ring/note in to her, but some can.<br>
   Unless they have done a radical new change in NPC code specificly for this quest, 1 npc can only give 2 responses to &quot;hail&quot; (or any single keyword).  One for insufficient faction, and one for sufficient.  It's possible that everyone is insufficient, and the bad faction message is actually the ring quest, but since you can gain truespirit a few places, this would be a bad idea (once you got high enough faction Arantir would suddenly ask for the 3 staves upon being hailed).<br>
  More likely is that the note (resulting from the bag which results from the skin) spawns an identically named NPC in the same spot, which is actually different.  You can see this behavior several places, most notable with Zordak Ragefire at the end of the cleric epic.  He's a level 60 (i believe?) merchant until you hand him the trigger item, then he instantly repops as level 55 and agro, he still has the same name and look though. (after you kill this repop a dragon pops, but that's beside the point).<br>
  Note that if this &quot;new&quot; arantir were the same as the old, and handing the note did &quot;change&quot; the message he gave you (or being the first to hail him) - he wouldn't just not talk to you if you didn't hand in the note.  Instead he would give you the ring quest he normally does when you hail him.<br>
  What about the other fellow though?  The one that said someone else hailed him first.  I'd imagine he didn't have sufficient faction.  Maybe he skipped parts of the quest, maybe he killed a key npc, maybe he did a thousand things, but recall that he never finished the quest himself.  The GM reimbursed him not with the pieces to turn in again, but with the final item.  Had he been reimbursed with all the pieces, Arantir would still have failed to talk to him.  I'd go so far as to wager that someone else had the cazic skin, bag, and then note, and he was trying a quest swap (hush hush, no one at verant has said this is an exploit, but if you bring it up too much they might decide to speak.. verant never speaks for players, they're either silent, or against).<br>
  So the point of this?  Is this just a wild goose chase, or can you use any of the information here?  Of course you can!  I'd suggest that should you aquire the skin, you hang onto those very nice mid-quest staves until several of your friends have all three staves as well (note that I said friends, as in people that wont try to screw you over :P).  Then get those poor saps to bump their truespirit faction to high hell.  I believe the only &quot;open faction gain&quot; portion of our quest is giving 1000 pp to camin.  That can be a bit expensive, but maybe you have some friends that ran the note loop back before the whole quest was shut off to fix these faction holes.  In any event, once they have high faction (don't worry about your own, you're doing this straight through and should be reimbursed if it fails) go turn in your note.  Make sure you hail him first, and turn in your staves.  Once you're done, have the others hail him and see if they get the &quot;give me your staves&quot; message as well.  If it works, your friends will be happy, if it doesn't, no one has lost anything.<br>
  You may also want to Con arantir (in his various incarnations) before and after handing in items.  If the note takes you from apprehensive to warmly, your friends would probably need warmly to procede as well.<br>
<br>
<br>
Rhad<br>
